(44, 12, 11, 42, 15, 17, 17, NULL, 'Self-Realization in Crisis', 'This connection highlights moments of self-awareness in times of distress. Both Peter and the prodigal son come to themselves, recognizing their dire situations and the need for divine intervention or return to a better state.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 12, 62, 5, 14, 15, 'gathered together praying', 'Prayer and Divine Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of prayer and the assurance of God hearing those prayers. In Acts 12:12, believers are gathered together praying, while 1 John 5:14-15 emphasizes confidence that God hears and responds to prayers made according to His will.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 12, 44, 12, 5, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Prayer and Deliverance', 'Both passages emphasize the role of prayer in Peter''s deliverance from prison. In Acts 12:5, the church prays ceaselessly for him, and in Acts 12:12, the gathering at Mary''s house indicates the continuation of this prayer effort.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 12, 23, 65, 24, 24, 'gathered together praying', 'Prayer and Divine Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of prayer and God''s responsiveness. In Acts, the believers are gathered together praying, while Isaiah emphasizes that God answers even before they call.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 12, 40, 18, 19, 20, 'gathered together praying', 'Gathering in Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of gathering together in prayer. Acts 12:12 describes a group praying, while Matthew 18:19-20 highlights the power of agreement in prayer among those gathered.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 12, 44, 12, 25, 25, 'John, whose surname was Mark', 'Connection of John Mark', 'This connection highlights the presence of John, whose surname was Mark, in both passages. In Acts 12:12, he is mentioned as part of a prayer gathering, while in Acts 12:25, he is noted as accompanying Barnabas and Saul after their ministry.', 'keyword', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 12, 55, 4, 11, 11, 'Mark', 'Connection Between Mark and Ministry', 'This connection highlights the significance of Mark in the early church. Both passages emphasize Mark''s role, first as a figure in prayer and later as someone deemed ''profitable'' for ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 12, 57, 1, 24, 24, 'John, whose surname was Mark', 'Connection through John Mark', 'This connection highlights the presence of John Mark, mentioned in Acts as the son of Mary, and his association with Paul in Philemon. Both passages emphasize the role of Mark as a fellow laborer in the early church.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 13, 42, 13, 25, 25, NULL, 'Knocking at the Door', 'This connection highlights the act of knocking at the door in both passages. In Acts, Rhoda hears Peter knocking, while in Luke, individuals knock seeking access, emphasizing themes of invitation and rejection.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 13, 44, 12, 16, 16, NULL, 'Peter''s Knocking at the Door', 'This connection highlights the act of Peter knocking at the door in both passages. The repetition of Peter''s knocking emphasizes the anticipation and eventual astonishment of those inside when they realize he is at the gate.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 13, 43, 18, 16, 17, 'damsel came to hearken', 'Peter at the Door', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s presence at a door, highlighting moments of recognition and denial. In Acts, Rhoda hears Peter knocking, while in John, a damsel questions Peter''s identity at the door.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 14, 42, 24, 41, 41, NULL, 'Joy and Belief Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of joy leading to disbelief. In both passages, characters experience overwhelming joy that causes them to struggle with belief in the miraculous events occurring before them.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 14, 40, 28, 8, 8, NULL, 'Joyful Responses to Good News', 'This connection highlights the theme of joy in response to significant news. Both passages depict individuals who, filled with joy, run to share important messages with others.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 15, 40, 18, 10, 10, 'It is his angel', 'Angels and Their Role', 'This connection highlights the presence of angels in both passages. In Acts, the mention of ''his angel'' suggests a belief in guardian angels, while Matthew emphasizes that ''their angels'' are in the presence of God.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 15, 41, 16, 11, 11, NULL, 'Unbelief in Resurrection Accounts', 'Both passages emphasize the disbelief of witnesses regarding the resurrection. In Acts, the response to the news of Peter''s escape mirrors the skepticism found in Mark about Jesus'' resurrection.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 15, 42, 24, 11, 11, NULL, 'Responses to Unbelievable News', 'Both passages emphasize disbelief in extraordinary claims. In Acts, the response to Peter''s miraculous escape is met with skepticism, similar to how the resurrection news is dismissed in Luke.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 12, 15, 42, 24, 37, 38, 'Thou art mad', 'Fear and Perception of Spirits', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear and misunderstanding regarding spiritual beings. Both passages depict individuals who are troubled and assume they are encountering a spirit or angel.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
